10 Tempat untuk Melihat Seni Leonardo da Vinci
Gambar Jonathan Stern
Jonathan Stern
Diperbarui: 14 Oktober 2016
Karya Leonardo da Vinci memiliki dampak yang tak terukur pada dunia seni Barat. Saat ini, sebagian besar karyanya ditemukan di kota-kota di Italia, seperti Florence dan Milan. Tetapi ada beberapa lainnya yang tersebar di kota-kota di seluruh dunia. Di sini, kami melihat sepuluh tempat di mana Anda dapat menemukan karya Leonardo.
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan, Italia
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan, Italia | © Marcin Białek / WikiCommons
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan
Leonardo melukis karya terkenal di dunia yang dikenal sebagai Il Cenacolo, atau 'Perjamuan Terakhir', di dinding di biara Dominika yang berdampingan dengan gereja Santa Maria delle Grazie di Milan, Italia. Dalam mengeksekusi 'Perjamuan Terakhir', Leonardo menggunakan teknik baru yang disebut secco, yang berarti bahwa ia melukisnya di dinding yang kering. Sayangnya, karena kombinasi dari seniman yang menggunakan teknik dan faktor lingkungan ini, pekerjaan ini telah melihat bagian kerusakannya selama bertahun-tahun. Hari-hari ini, untuk menjaga ruangan pada suhu yang sesuai, hanya 25 orang sekaligus diizinkan untuk melihatnya! (Jadi, pastikan untuk memesan dulu).
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Piazza Santa Maria delle Grazie, 2, Milan, Italia
Krak & # xF3; w, Muzeum Czartoryskich
Kraków, Muzeum Czartoryskich | © Fotopolska.eu/Danuta B / WikiCommons
Museum Czartoryski, Krakow
Museum ini didirikan pada 1796 oleh Putri Izabela Czartoryski untuk melestarikan warisan Polandia. Dua tahun setelah pendiriannya, putra Putri Czartoryski melakukan perjalanan ke Italia, di mana dia membeli lukisan Leonardo yang berjudul ‘Lady with an Ermine’. Selama periode itu, museum itu terletak di Pulawy; baru pada tahun 1878 ia pindah ke lokasinya yang sekarang di Krakow. Hari-hari ini, mahakarya da Vinci ini untuk sementara dapat dilihat di Wawel Royal Castle, sementara renovasi sedang dilakukan di rumah permanennya di pinggir jalan.
Museum Czartoryski, św. Jana 19, Krakow, Polandia, +48 12 370 5460
Courtyard of the Museum of Louvre, dan piramidanya
Courtyard of the Museum of Louvre, dan piramida | © Benh LIEU SONG / WikiCommons
Louvre, Paris
Salah satu museum terbesar di dunia, The Louvre adalah monumen dan landmark utama di Paris. Ini adalah rumah bagi koleksi besar-besaran karya seni, termasuk ikon Leonardo 'Mona Lisa', lukisan Italia paling awal untuk fokus serius pada pengasuh dalam potret setengah panjang. Bagaimana cara kerja yang begitu penting oleh guru Renaissance Italia berakhir di Prancis? Alih-alih memberikan potret kepada orang yang menugaskannya, Leonardo kemungkinan membawa karya yang telah selesai ke Prancis. Setelah kematian artis, ‘Mona Lisa’ memasuki koleksi kerajaan Francis I.
Louvre, 75001 Paris, Prancis, +33 1 40 20 5050
Galeri Uffizi, Florence
Galeri Uffizi, Florence | © Chris Wee / WikiCommons
Galeri Uffizi, Florence
Hall 15 Galeri Uffizi adalah tempat yang harus dilihat berkat pameran karya-karyanya oleh Leonardo da Vinci muda. Lukisan-lukisan ini semua selesai sebelum 1482, tahun Leonardo meninggalkan Florence untuk melukis untuk Duke Ludovico il Moro di Milan. Di ruangan ini, pengunjung dapat melihat tahap awal kecemerlangan artis selama waktu ketika dia magang di bawah guru besar Andrea del Verocchio. ‘Annunciation’ dan ‘Adoration of the Magi’ adalah dua hal penting yang membuktikan perhatian ilmiahnya terhadap detail, teknik menggambar yang dinamis dan kemampuan luar biasa untuk membuat latar belakang lanskap.
Galeri Uffizi, Piazzale degli Uffizi, 6, Florence, Italia, +39 055 238 8651
Galeri Nasional, London, Inggris
Galeri Nasional, London, Inggris | © Diego Delso / WikiCommons
Galeri Nasional, London
Galeri Nasional di London adalah rumah bagi dua karya penting oleh Leonardo: ‘The Virgin of the Rocks’ dan ‘The Burlington House Cartoon’, dibeli oleh museum pada tahun 1880 dan 1962. Museum ini didirikan pada tahun 1824 dan menyimpan koleksi lebih dari 2.300 lukisan - koleksi yang menjadi milik publik Kerajaan Inggris. Akibatnya, pengunjung ke museum dapat menikmati karya seni yang spektakuler, seperti dua karya Leonardo, gratis. Rata-rata, museum melihat lebih dari 6 juta pengunjung per tahun!
Galeri Nasional, Trafalgar Square, London, Inggris, +44 20 7747 2885
Gedung Barat Galeri Seni Nasional
Gedung Barat Galeri Seni Nasional | © AgnosticPreachersKid / Wikicommons
Galeri Seni Nasional, Washington DC
Museum nasional lain yang cukup beruntung untuk memiliki karya da Vinci dalam koleksinya adalah Galeri Seni Nasional di Washington DC. Bahkan, ‘Ginevra de’ Benci ’adalah satu-satunya lukisan karya Leonardo dalam pandangan publik di Benua Amerika. Potret itu adalah salah satu eksperimen pertama Leonardo dengan lukisan cat minyak; ada beberapa kerutan di panel yang mengungkapkan dia masih berusaha mengendalikannya. Galeri membeli potret pada tahun 1967 dengan harga $ 5 juta - harga rekor pada saat itu.
Galeri Seni Nasional, Konstitusi 6 & Konstitusi Ave NW, Washington, DC, AS, +1 202 737 4215
The Sistine Hall dari Perpustakaan Vatikan | © russavia / WikiCommons
Museum Vatikan, Roma
‘St. Jerome in the Wilderness ’, lukisan yang belum selesai oleh Leonardo, terletak di Museum Vatikan di Roma. Ini menunjukkan Saint Jerome berlutut di lanskap berbatu, melihat ke arah salib yang telah samar-samar sketsa di bagian kanan atas lukisan itu. Singa berbaring di kakinya. Museum-museum ini, didirikan pada awal abad ke-16, menampilkan koleksi besar-besaran karya seni yang dikumpulkan oleh para paus sepanjang abad. Selain Leonardo, ada sejumlah seniman Italia penting lainnya yang diwakili di sini, termasuk Giotto, Raphael, Michelangelo, dan Caravaggio untuk menyebut hanya beberapa.
Museum Vatikan, Viale Vaticano, Roma, Italia, +39 06 6988 3332
Alte Pinakothek, Munich
Alte Pinakothek, Munich | © Markus Würfel / WikiCommons
Alte Pinakothek, Munich
Alte Pinakothek dari Munich adalah salah satu galeri seni tertua di dunia, yang menampung koleksi lukisan tuan tua yang mengesankan. Gaya arsitektur Renaissance Renaissance bangunan adalah karya seni itu sendiri. Koleksi yang menonjol adalah Leonardo 'Madonna of the Carnation', yang telah dipamerkan di sini sejak tahun 1889. Meskipun pada awalnya dikaitkan dengan Andrea del Verocchio, sekarang para sejarawan seni setuju bahwa itu memang karya Leonardo. Ini adalah satu-satunya karya seni oleh guru Italia yang ditampilkan secara permanen di Jerman.
Alte Pinakothek, Barer Str. 27, Munich, Jerman, +49 89 23805216
Gallerie dell'Accademia, Venesia
Gallerie dell'Accademia di Venesia beruntung menyebut dirinya rumah lukisan tinta 'Virtuvian Man' karya Leonardo yang terkenal di dunia. Seperti kebanyakan gambar yang dibuat dengan tinta, studi geometrik Leonardo tentang proporsi tubuh manusia hanya ditampilkan pada kesempatan langka. Tetapi itu tidak berarti galeri ini tidak layak untuk dikunjungi. Koleksinya juga menawarkan karya-karya dari Venetian provenance hingga abad ke-18, termasuk karya-karya seniman seperti Tintoretto, Titian dan Giorgione.
Galleria dell'Accademia, Campo della Carità, 1050, Venesia, Italia, +39 041 520 0345
Museum Hermitage, Saint Petersburg
Sebuah karya Leonardo di Rusia? Ya, itu benar - kunjungi Hermitage Museum yang tampak mengesankan di Saint Petersburg untuk melihat 'The Madonna Litta'. Meskipun atribusi lukisan berada di bawah beberapa sengketa, museum bersikeras dalam menyatakan bahwa pekerjaan itu dilakukan oleh Leonardo. Lukisan itu berakhir di Rusia melalui Count Litta Milan, yang menjual empat karya ke Museum Hermitage, termasuk yang satu ini, pada Januari 1865. Setelah mendapatkannya, museum memindahkannya dari panel kayu ke kanvas.
Hermitage Museum, Palace Square, 2, St Petersburg, Rusia, +7 812 710 9079

10 Places to See the Art of Leonardo da Vinci
Picture of Jonathan Stern
Jonathan Stern
Updated: 14 October 2016
Leonardo da Vinci‘s work had an immeasurable impact on the world of Western art. Today, the majority of his works are found in cities in Italy, such as Florence and Milan. But there are a few others scattered in cities across the globe. Here, we take a look at ten places where you can find a Leonardo masterpiece.
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan, Italy
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan, Italy | ©Marcin Białek/WikiCommons
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Milan
Leonardo painted the world famous work known as Il Cenacolo, or the ‘Last Supper’, on a wall in the Dominican convent adjoining the church of Santa Maria delle Grazie in Milan, Italy. In executing the ‘Last Supper’, Leonardo used a new technique called a secco, meaning that he painted it on a dry wall. Unfortunately, due to a combination of the artist employing this technique and environmental factors, the work has seen its share of deterioration over the years. These days, in order to keep the room at a suitable temperature, only 25 people at a time are permitted to view it! (So, be sure to book ahead).
Santa Maria delle Grazie, Piazza Santa Maria delle Grazie, 2, Milan, Italy
Krak&#xF3;w, Muzeum Czartoryskich
Kraków, Muzeum Czartoryskich | © Fotopolska.eu/Danuta B/WikiCommons
Czartoryski Museum, Krakow
This museum was founded in 1796 by Princess Izabela Czartoryski to preserve Polish heritage. Two years after its establishment, Princess Czartoryski’s son traveled to Italy, where he purchased Leonardo’s portrait called ‘Lady with an Ermine’. During that period, the museum was located in Pulawy; it was not until 1878 that it made its move to its present-day location in Krakow. These days, this da Vinci masterpiece can temporarily be seen at the Wawel Royal Castle, while renovations are being carried out at its permanent home just up the road.
Czartoryski Museum, św. Jana 19, Krakow, Poland, +48 12 370 5460
Courtyard of the Museum of Louvre, and its pyramid
Courtyard of the Museum of Louvre, and its pyramid | © Benh LIEU SONG/WikiCommons
The Louvre, Paris
One of the largest museums in the world, The Louvre is a monument and central landmark in Paris. It is home to a massive collection of artwork, including Leonardo’s iconic ‘Mona Lisa’, the earliest Italian painting to focus intently on the sitter in a half-length portrait. How did such an important work by the Italian Renaissance master end up in France? Rather than giving the portrait to the person who commissioned it, Leonardo likely brought the completed work to France. After the artist’s death, the ‘Mona Lisa’ entered the royal collection of Francis I.
The Louvre, 75001 Paris, France, +33 1 40 20 5050
Uffizi Gallery, Florence
Uffizi Gallery, Florence | © Chris Wee/WikiCommons
Uffizi Gallery, Florence
Hall 15 of the Uffizi Gallery is a must-see thanks to its display of works by a young Leonardo da Vinci. These paintings were all completed before 1482, the year Leonardo left Florence to paint for Duke Ludovico il Moro in Milan. In this room, visitors can view the early stages of the artist’s brilliance during a time when he apprenticed under the great master Andrea del Verocchio. ‘Annunciation’ and ‘Adoration of the Magi’ are two of the highlights that evidence his scientific attention to detail, dynamic drawing technique and amazing ability to render landscape backgrounds.
Uffizi Gallery, Piazzale degli Uffizi, 6, Florence, Italy, +39 055 238 8651
National Gallery, London, England
National Gallery, London, England | © Diego Delso/WikiCommons
National Gallery, London
The National Gallery in London is home to two important works by Leonardo: ‘The Virgin of the Rocks’ and ‘The Burlington House Cartoon’, purchased by the museum in 1880 and 1962 respectively. The museum was founded in 1824 and houses a collection of more than 2,300 paintings in total – a collection that belongs to the public of the United Kingdom. As a result, visitors to the museum can enjoy spectacular artwork, like the two Leonardo masterpieces, for free. On average, the museum sees more than 6 million visitors per year!
National Gallery, Trafalgar Square, London, United Kingdom, +44 20 7747 2885
West Building of the National Gallery of Art
West Building of the National Gallery of Art | ©AgnosticPreachersKid/Wikicommons
National Gallery of Art, Washington DC
Another national museum lucky enough to have a da Vinci work in its collection is the National Gallery of Art in Washington DC. In fact, ‘Ginevra de’ Benci’ is the only painting by Leonardo on public view in the Americas. The portrait was one of Leonardo’s first experiments with oil painting; there are a few wrinkles on the panel that reveal he was still endeavoring to control it. The gallery acquired the portrait in 1967 for a sum of $5 million – a record price at the time.
National Gallery of Art, 6th & Constitution Ave NW, Washington, DC, USA, +1 202 737 4215
The Sistine Hall of the Vatican Library
The Sistine Hall of the Vatican Library | ©russavia/WikiCommons
Vatican Museums, Rome
‘St. Jerome in the Wilderness’, an unfinished painting by Leonardo, is located in the Vatican Museums in Rome. It shows Saint Jerome kneeling in a rocky landscape, looking up toward a crucifix that has been faintly sketched at the top right portion of the painting. A lion lays at his feet. These museums, founded in the early 16th century, display the massive collection of artwork amassed by popes throughout the centuries. In addition to Leonardo, there are a number of other important Italian artists represented here, including Giotto, Raphael, Michelangelo and Caravaggio to name just a few.
Vatican Museums, Viale Vaticano, Rome, Italy, +39 06 6988 3332
Alte Pinakothek, Munich
Alte Pinakothek, Munich | © Markus Würfel/WikiCommons
Alte Pinakothek, Munich
Munich’s Alte Pinakothek is one of the oldest art galleries in the world, housing an impressive collection of old master paintings. The building’s Renaissance Revival architectural style is a work of art in itself. A standout of the collection is Leonardo’s ‘Madonna of the Carnation’, which has been on display here since 1889. Though it was originally attributed to Andrea del Verocchio, today art historians agree that it is indeed Leonardo’s work. It is the only work of art by the Italian master permanently displayed in Germany.
Alte Pinakothek, Barer Str. 27, Munich, Germany, +49 89 23805216
Gallerie dell’Accademia, Venice
Gallerie dell’Accademia in Venice is fortunate to call itself the home of Leonardo’s world-famous ‘Virtuvian Man’ ink drawing. Like most drawings done in ink, Leonardo’s geometric study of the proportions of the human body is displayed only on rare occasion. But that does not mean this gallery isn’t worth the visit. Its collection also boasts masterpieces of Venetian provenance up to the 18th century, including works by artists such as Tintoretto, Titian and Giorgione.
Galleria dell’Accademia, Campo della Carità, 1050, Venice, Italy, +39 041 520 0345
Hermitage Museum, Saint Petersburg
A work by Leonardo in Russia? Yes, it’s true – head to the impressive-looking Hermitage Museum in Saint Petersburg to see ‘The Madonna Litta’. Though the painting’s attribution is under some dispute, the museum is adamant in stating that the work was done by Leonardo. The painting ended up in Russia through Count Litta of Milan, who sold four works to the Hermitage Museum, including this one, in January 1865. Upon acquiring it, the museum transferred it from a wood panel to canvas.
Hermitage Museum, Palace Square, 2, St Petersburg, Russia, +7 812 710 9079
